"Catherine Everett looks at the important question of who is responsible for policing the global internet, and explores whether it is purely the remit of law enforcement agencies, or whether it is necessary for society at all levels to take individual and collective responsibility. She also looks at how, despite limited resources, the UK's newly created Police Central e-crime Unit is attempting to coordinate activity at a national level in this area and to work in collaboration with third party law enforcement agencies as well as industry to tackle the growing problem of cybercrime more effectively. An important question was posed at the Infosecurity conference in London at the end of April: who is ultimately responsible for policing the global internet?"
